[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-county-courthouse] The **Abbeville County Courthouse**, built in 1908, is an historic courthouse located in the east corner of Court Square, in the city of Abbeville in Abbeville County, South Carolina.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-county-courthouse] It was designed in the Beaux Arts style by Darlington native William Augustus Edwards who designed several other South Carolina courthouses as well as academic buildings at 12 institutions in Florida, Georgia and South Carolina.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-county-courthouse] An arcade connects it to the adjoining Abbeville Opera House and Municipal Center, which Edwards also designed.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-county-courthouse] In 1964, the courthouse was renovated by Lyles, Bissett, Carlisle, and Wolff of Columbia.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-county-courthouse] On October 30, 1981, it was added to the National Register of Historic Places.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-county-courthouse] It is included in the Abbeville Historic District.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-county-courthouse] The current courthouse is the sixth courthouse to serve Abbeville County.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-county-courthouse] Located inside the central hallway is a portrait of John C.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-county-courthouse] Calhoun, twice vice-president and longtime senator from South Carolina.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-county-courthouse] Calhoun was born southwest of the town on his father's plantation.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-county-courthouse] He practiced law for a short time on the county square.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-county-courthouse] The courthouse is located on land that once housed the law firm in which Calhoun practiced early in his career.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-county-south-carolina] Both Abbeville County and the county seat, Abbeville, get their name from the town of Abbeville, France, the native home of an early settler.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-county-south-carolina] The county was originally part of Ninety-Six District, South Carolina, but was designated Abbeville County in 1785, with parts of the county later going to the creation of the counties of Greenwood and McCormick.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-county-south-carolina] Abbeville County was settled by mostly Scotch Irish and French-Huguenot farmers in the mid-18th century.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-county-south-carolina] The Treaty of Dewitt's Corner, a historic peace negotiation with the Cherokee Indians, was signed in Dewitt's Corner (which is now known as Due West) in the county.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-county-south-carolina] As a result of the treaty, the Cherokee tribe broke into two factions, one of which, the Chickamauga Cherokee, continued fighting area settlers for another 30 years.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-county-south-carolina] Abbeville County was a hotbed of secession before the Civil War and was also where the last Confederate council of war was held.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-county-south-carolina] In 1950 Abbeville County had a population of 22,456.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-county-south-carolina] As of the 2020 census, this has grown to 24,295 people.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-county-south-carolina] There were nine documented lynchings in Abbeville, SC.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-county-south-carolina] Nelson known as "James Macon","James Mason", 1894.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-county-south-carolina] Anthony Crawford, a prominent landowner, farmer, businessman lynched for not selling his cotton at the price demanded.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-county-south-carolina] Abbeville County is in the Savannah River basin and the Saluda River basin.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-county-south-carolina] Note: the US Census treats Hispanic/Latino as an ethnic category.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-county-south-carolina] This table excludes Latinos from the racial categories and assigns them to a separate category.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-county-south-carolina] As of the 2020 census, the county had a population of 24,295, 9,818 households, and 6,248 families residing in the county.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-county-south-carolina] The median age was 45.0 years, with 20.3% of residents under the age of 18 and 22.6% of residents 65 years of age or older.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-county-south-carolina] For every 100 females there were 94.2 males, and for every 100 females age 18 and over there were 91.7 males age 18 and over.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-county-south-carolina] The 2020 PL data (see table) show the population remained predominantly White, with a large Black or African American minority and smaller American Indian and Alaska Native, Asian, Pacific Islander, and Hispanic or Latino communities.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-county-south-carolina] Twenty-one percent of residents lived in urban areas and 79.0% lived in rural areas.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-county-south-carolina] Of those households, 28.1% had children under the age of 18 living with them and 30.5% had a female householder with no spouse or partner present.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-county-south-carolina] About 28.7% of all households were made up of individuals, and 14.0% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-county-south-carolina] There were 11,540 housing units, of which 14.9% were vacant.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-county-south-carolina] Among occupied housing units, 77.2% were owner-occupied and 22.8% were renter-occupied, with the homeowner vacancy rate at 1.3% and the rental vacancy rate at 7.2%.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-county-south-carolina] At the 2010 census, there were 25,417 people, 9,990 households, and 6,939 families living in the county.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-county-south-carolina] The population density was 51.8 inhabitants per square mile (20.0/km2).
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-county-south-carolina] There were 12,079 housing units at an average density of 24.6 units per square mile (9.5 units/km2).
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-county-south-carolina] The racial makeup of the county was 69.6% white, 28.3% black or African American, 0.3% Asian, 0.2% American Indian, 0.4% from other races, and 1.1% from two or more races.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-county-south-carolina] Those of Hispanic or Latino origin made up 1.0% of the population.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-county-south-carolina] In terms of ancestry, 14.7% were American, 10.9% were Irish, 9.7% were English, 7.6% were German, and 5.6% were Scotch-Irish.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-county-south-carolina] Of the 9,990 households, 31.5% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 49.2% were married couples living together, 15.3% had a female householder with no husband present, 30.5% were non-families, and 27.3% of all households were made up of individuals.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-county-south-carolina] The average household size was 2.45 and the average family size was 2.98.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-county-south-carolina] The median income for a household in the county was $33,143 and the median income for a family was $45,147.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-county-south-carolina] Males had a median income of $39,217 versus $29,199 for females.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-county-south-carolina] The per capita income for the county was $16,653.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-county-south-carolina] About 16.3% of families and 20.7% of the population were below the poverty line, including 26.8% of those under age 18 and 16.2% of those age 65 or over.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-county-south-carolina] At the 2000 census, there were 26,167 people, 10,131 households, and 7,284 families living in the county.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-county-south-carolina] The population density was 52 people per square mile (20 people/km2).
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-county-south-carolina] There were 11,656 housing units at an average density of 23 units per square mile (8.9 units/km2).
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-county-south-carolina] The racial makeup of the county was 68.33% White, 30.29% Black or African American, 0.10% Native American, 0.23% Asian, 0.03% Pacific Islander, 0.31% from other races, and 0.71% from two or more races.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-county-south-carolina] 0.83% of the population were Hispanic or Latino of any race.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-county-south-carolina] 22.1% were of American, 9.7% Irish, 6.7% English, 5.5% German and 5.3% Scotch-Irish ancestry according to Census 2000.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-county-south-carolina] There were 10,131 households, out of which 31.70% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 52.20% were married couples living together, 15.30% had a female householder with no husband present, and 28.10% were non-families.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-county-south-carolina] 25.30% of all households were made up of individuals, and 11.30% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-county-south-carolina] The average household size was 2.51 and the average family size was 3.00.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-county-south-carolina] In the county, the population was spread out, with 25.30% under the age of 18, 9.50% from 18 to 24, 26.70% from 25 to 44, 23.80% from 45 to 64, and 14.70% who were 65 years of age or older.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-county-south-carolina] For every 100 females there were 92.10 males.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-county-south-carolina] For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 88.00 males.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-county-south-carolina] The median income for a household in the county was $32,635, and the median income for a family was $38,847.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-county-south-carolina] Males had a median income of $30,452 versus $21,045 for females.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-county-south-carolina] The per capita income for the county was $15,370.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-county-south-carolina] About 10.10% of families and 13.70% of the population were below the poverty line, including 17.20% of those under age 18 and 16.90% of those age 65 or over.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-county-south-carolina] Norris is the chairman of the Abbeville County Council, who also represents district 4.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-county-south-carolina] In 2013, long-time Abbeville County Sheriff Charles Goodwin pled guilty to misconduct in office.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-county-south-carolina] He was put on probation for five years, sentenced to 100 hours of community service, and ordered to pay $4,500 in restitution.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-county-south-carolina] Abbeville County was a typical "Solid South" county in its voting patterns until 1948 when it voted for Dixiecrat candidate and South Carolina native Strom Thurmond against Democratic candidate Harry Truman regarding his support for Civil Rights, most importantly racial integration.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-county-south-carolina] It resumed voting Democratic until 1968 when a majority voted for American Independent Party candidate & southern segregationist George Wallace.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-county-south-carolina] In 1972 the county voted overwhelmingly for Richard Nixon, and since then Abbeville has showed strong endorsement towards the Republican Party.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-county-south-carolina] The last Democrat to carry Abbeville County was Bill Clinton in 1992 and 1996.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-county-south-carolina] In 1999, Abbeville County had the highest level of economic development and job creation per capita in all of South Carolina.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-county-south-carolina] Throughout 2023 and early 2024, the unemployment rate of Abbeville has fluctuated around 4%.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-county-south-carolina] In 2022, the GDP of Abbeville County was $666.9 million (roughly $27,450 per capita).
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-county-south-carolina] In chained 2017 dollars, its per-capita real GDP was $22,685.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-county-south-carolina] According to the Bureau of Labor Statistics, Abbeville has 417 employment establishments (private and public organizations covered by unemployment insurance).
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-county-south-carolina] As of Q3 2023, some of the top 20 employers in the state include the city of Abbeville, Erskine College, Hardee's, Ingles, Prysmian Group, Sage Automotive Interiors, and Wayfair.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-county-south-carolina] There are two school districts in the county: Abbeville County School District takes up the majority of the area, while some parts are in the Greenwood School District 51.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-county-south-carolina] Most Abbeville County schools are part of the Abbeville County School District.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-historic-district-abbeville-south-carolina] Originally, the district was roughly bounded by Seaboard Coastline RR, SR 72, Rickey, Haight, Hemphill and Haigler Sts.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-historic-district-abbeville-south-carolina] A 1972 decrease of area, roughly E of Magazine St., S of Whitehall St., NW along Long Branch St., W of Lemon St., N along Washington St., decreased the size of the district.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-historic-district-abbeville-south-carolina] According to the National Register Information System (NRIS), this decrease was approved simultaneously as the original district designation.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-historic-district-abbeville-south-carolina] A 1984 increase, of area roughly W along N.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-historic-district-abbeville-south-carolina] Main St. from Haigler to Livingston Sts., N along Greenville St., and NE on Marshall Ct., added to the district.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-historic-district-abbeville-south-carolina] The district includes a large portion of Abbeville, the county seat of Abbeville County.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-historic-district-abbeville-south-carolina] The city, formed in the late 18th century, played a role in the political history of the area, including one of the first public meetings regarding succession from the Union, a precursor to the Civil War.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-historic-district-abbeville-south-carolina] Most of the commercial buildings in the district are representative of the late 19th and early 20th centuries, primarily due to three large fires in 1872 - 1873.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-historic-district-abbeville-south-carolina] The subsequent redevelopment gave the town square its present appearance.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-historic-district-abbeville-south-carolina] The original nomination form included sixteen sites that contributed to the historical significance of the district.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-historic-district-abbeville-south-carolina] The boundary increase that occurred on May 7, 1984, added numerous properties to the district.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-historic-district-abbeville-south-carolina] The district now contains 37 properties of significance, 282 supporting properties, and 209 non-contributing properties for a total of 528 sites.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-historic-district-abbeville-south-carolina] Most of the structures are still standing, although the addresses used in the nomination form may have changed.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-opera-house] The **Abbeville Opera House**, also known as the **Abbeville Opera House and Municipal Office Building** is an historic building located in Abbeville, South Carolina.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-opera-house] Designed by William Augustus Edwards of Edwards and Wilson, it was opened in 1904 and dedicated in 1908.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-opera-house] On July 1, 1970, it was added to the National Register of Historic Places.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-opera-house] According to the South Carolina Department of Parks, Recreation and Tourism the theater has received the South Carolina Governor's Travel Award for Tourism and was designated as the Official Rural Drama State Theatre of South Carolina.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-opera-house] At the turn of the 20th century there were many "road companies" producing shows in New York City.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-opera-house] Once the production was assembled, the show traveled throughout the country.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-opera-house] One of the more popular tours went from New York to Richmond to Atlanta.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-opera-house] For a number of years, Abbeville was an overnight stop for the entire touring company.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-opera-house] Several members of the community decided that if this area had a facility, since the travelling companies were coming through the area anyway, Abbeville could sponsor some of these touring productions.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-opera-house] On October 1, 1908, what was then the Abbeville District dedicated a new Abbeville County Courthouse and City Hall.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-opera-house] The grand old theatre now known as the Abbeville Opera House was a part of that splendid pair of buildings "equal in beauty of architecture and modern conveniences of any in the state," according to regional newspaper accounts of the day.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-opera-house] From that time on, all the "greats and near greats" played on the magnificent Opera House stage.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-opera-house] Vaudeville was in its "heyday" as was Abbeville and the Abbeville Opera House.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-opera-house] Today, most people who visit the historic Abbeville Opera House see a building that represents a microcosm of the history of Abbeville since the turn-of-the-century.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-opera-house] Efforts toward preservation and renewal of Abbeville and the renewal of the Abbeville Opera House began some thirty years ago.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-opera-house] The refurbished theatre operates year-round.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-opera-house] The 218 newly refurbished seats face a 7,800-square-foot (720 m2) stage.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-opera-house] The balcony has 92 seats and the turn of the 20th century boxes seat up to 6 people in each of the four box seats.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-south-carolina] Abbeville was established by French Huguenots in 1764, at a site named by John de la Howe.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-south-carolina] Famed states' rights advocate and Vice President John C.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-south-carolina] Calhoun first practiced law in Abbeville, and he was born on a farm on the outskirts in what is now Mt.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-south-carolina] Abbeville has the unique distinction of being both the birthplace and the deathbed of the Confederacy.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-south-carolina] On November 22, 1860, a meeting was held at Abbeville, at a site since dubbed "Secession Hill", to launch South Carolina's secession from the Union; one month later, the state of South Carolina became the first state to secede.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-south-carolina] At the end of the Civil War, with the Confederacy in shambles, Confederate President Jefferson Davis fled Richmond, Virginia, and headed south, stopping for a night in Abbeville at the home of his friend Armistead Burt.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-south-carolina] It was on May 2, 1865, in the front parlor of what is now known as the Burt-Stark Mansion that Jefferson Davis officially acknowledged the dissolution of the Confederate government, in the last official cabinet meeting.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-south-carolina] On December 8, 2003, in a 14-hour standoff that stemmed from a land-survey dispute, two Abbeville lawmen were killed by West Abbeville resident Steven Bixby.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-south-carolina] This siege has been compared by both sympathizers of the Bixbys and law enforcement agents to the events of Waco and Ruby Ridge.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-south-carolina] In February 2007, Steven Bixby was convicted on 17 counts including the two murders, as well as lesser charges of kidnapping and conspiracy.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-south-carolina] He was given two death sentences for the murders plus 125 years in prison on the other charges.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-south-carolina] Abbeville is also the location of the tallest building in South Carolina, the Prysmian Copper Wire Tower.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-south-carolina] Built in 2009, the tower is 373 feet (114 m) tall and has 30 floors.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-south-carolina] Abbeville is located within the Piedmont Upland geographical region.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-south-carolina] According to the United States Census Bureau, the city has a total area of 6.1 square miles (15.9 km2), of which 0.012 square miles (0.03 km2), or 0.19%, is water.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-south-carolina] Abbeville has a humid subtropical climate (Köppen *Cfa*).
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-south-carolina] Winters are cool, sometimes cold, and short in duration.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-south-carolina] The transitional seasons of spring and fall can vary in temperature but tend to be warm.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-south-carolina] In the summer highs usually peak in the mid 90s, but temperatures over 100 °F (37.8 °C) occur on occasion, most recently in the summer of 2012 during a heat wave.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-south-carolina] That year, the all-time record high of 109 °F (42.8 °C) was recorded on July 1.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-south-carolina] In the winter highs are in the low- to mid-50s and lows are right around freezing, seldom dropping below 25 °F (−3.9 °C).
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-south-carolina] Precipitation is well distributed throughout the year.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-south-carolina] Afternoon thunderstorms are a common occurrence in the summer months and can bring heavy winds and lightning.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-south-carolina] On March 31, 1973, an F4 tornado struck Abbeville and killed 7 people, making it the deadliest single tornado in 1973.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-south-carolina] The area was struck by two tornadoes on April 10, 2009.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-south-carolina] No fatalities were recorded, but the majority of the city lost power and many buildings sustained significant damage.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-south-carolina] Abbeville first appeared in the 1850 U.S.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-south-carolina] Census, when the town recorded a population of 1,252.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-south-carolina] As of the 2020 census, Abbeville had a population of 4,874.
