[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-south-carolina] The racial makeup of the city was 50.46% White, 48.48% African American, 0.12% Native American, 0.26% Asian, 0.02% Pacific Islander, 0.19% from other races, and 0.48% from two or more races.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-south-carolina] Hispanic or Latino of any race were 0.75% of the population.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-south-carolina] There were 2,396 households, out of which 30.7% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 37.1% were married couples living together, 23.9% had a female householder with no husband present, and 34.3% were non-families.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-south-carolina] 30.6% of all households were made up of individuals, and 13.9% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-south-carolina] The average household size was 2.39 and the average family size was 2.97.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-south-carolina] In the city, the population was spread out, with 27.2% under the age of 18, 8.8% from 18 to 24, 25.9% from 25 to 44, 21.2% from 45 to 64, and 16.8% who were 65 years of age or older.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-south-carolina] For every 100 females, there were 80.4 males.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-south-carolina] For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 73.9 males.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-south-carolina] The median income for a household in the city was $25,756, and the median income for a family was $30,040.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-south-carolina] Males had a median income of $28,339 versus $21,824 for females.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-south-carolina] The per capita income for the city was $13,274.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-south-carolina] About 16.3% of families and 19.8% of the population were below the poverty line, including 29.2% of those under age 18 and 20.9% of those age 65 or over.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-south-carolina] Abbeville is the center of a small urban cluster with a total population of 6,038 (2000 census).
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-south-carolina] Agriculture and forestry are important industries in the area.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-south-carolina] Crops that are grown in quantities are cotton, corn, wheat, and hay.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-south-carolina] Livestock, dairy cows, and poultry are also raised in the area.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-south-carolina] Finally, textiles are the chief manufactured product, in particular, clothing.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-south-carolina] After the North American Free Trade Agreement clothing is no longer made in Abbeville.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-south-carolina] Also represented are plastic and metal products.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-south-carolina] Abbeville is in the Abbeville County School District.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-south-carolina] Abbeville has Long Cane Primary, Westwood Elementary, J.S.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-south-carolina] Wright Middle, Dixie High, and Abbeville High for schools.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-south-carolina] Abbeville has a public library, a branch of the Abbeville County Library System.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-south-carolina] It also has some colleges, such as Piedmont Tech, Lander, Erskine, and many more.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-south-carolina] Abbeville is the homeplace of a holiday pudding dessert called Gypsy.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-south-carolina] Gypsy consists of pound or sponge cake, boiled custard, sherry, whipping cream, and almonds.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-south-carolina] Variations of recipe substituting bourbon for sherry exist.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-south-carolina] It resembles English trifle and has been referred to as "tipsy pudding" and southern tiramisu.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-south-carolina] It is usually cooked for Thanksgiving and/or Christmas in many "old Abbeville" families.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-south-carolina] The dish is not known to exist outside of Abbeville other than in families who moved from Abbeville elsewhere.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-south-carolina] It is usually served in a special stemmed, medium-sized, decorative crystal compote.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-south-carolina] The origins of Gypsy go back to late 19th century.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-south-carolina] There is a mention of *Gispy cake* in 1831 edition William Kitchiner's *The Cook's Oracle,* which may have been a prototype for the Abbeville Gypsy.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/abbeville-south-carolina] A local legend tells a story of an unknown woman serving Gypsy to Confederate President Jefferson Davis at the end of the Civil War in 1865.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/agnes-scott-college] The college was founded in 1889 as **Decatur Female Seminary** by Presbyterian minister Frank Henry Gaines.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/agnes-scott-college] In 1890, the name was changed to **Agnes Scott Institute** to honor the mother of the college's primary benefactor, Col.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/agnes-scott-college] The name was changed again to Agnes Scott College in 1906 and remains today a women's college.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/agnes-scott-college] Agnes Scott is considered the first higher education institution in the state of Georgia to receive regional accreditation.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/agnes-scott-college] The ninth and current president since July 2018 is Leocadia I.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/agnes-scott-college] Zak, who previously worked as director of the U.S.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/agnes-scott-college] On July 27, 1994, the campus was listed on the National Register of Historic Places as part of the *South Candler Street-Agnes Scott College Historic District*.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/agnes-scott-college] The historic district boundaries are East College Ave., South McDonough St., S.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/agnes-scott-college] Candler St., East Hill St. and East Davis St.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/agnes-scott-college] It includes the entire campus, as well as historic homes adjacent to the campus.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/agnes-scott-college] The campus is also designated by the City of Decatur as a historic district.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/agnes-scott-college] The Reverend Frank Henry Gaines served as the first President of Agnes Scott, formally known as Decatur Female Seminary School, for 27 years (1896–1923).
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/agnes-scott-college] During his 27-year presidency, he ensured stability and success for the school, including the transition to the collegiate level, accreditation by the Southern Association of Colleges and Schools, acquisition of 20 acres of land and 21 buildings and an increase in assets from $5,000 to $1.5 million.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/agnes-scott-college] Agnes Scott College is located within walking distance of downtown Decatur.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/agnes-scott-college] It is served by Decatur station on the MARTA rail system, which is also a hub for buses, allowing students to travel to the greater Atlanta area.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/agnes-scott-college] Agnes Scott occupies more than 90 acres (360,000 m2) in Decatur.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/agnes-scott-college] The college also owns the Avery Glen apartments as well as more than a dozen houses in the surrounding neighborhoods housing faculty, staff, and students.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/agnes-scott-college] There are also six dedicated undergraduate dormitories located on campus.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/agnes-scott-college] American poet Robert Frost was first invited to speak at Agnes Scott in 1935, by English professor Emma May Laney, and he visited the college every winter from 1945 until his death in 1963.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/agnes-scott-college] During his visits, he would read poetry in Presser Hall.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/agnes-scott-college] A statue of the poet sculpted by George W.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/agnes-scott-college] A collection of Robert Frost's poetry and letters can be viewed on the second floor of the McCain Library.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/agnes-scott-college] Agnes Scott (Main) Hall, named after Agnes Irvine Scott, is located at the center of "the main loop" and is a one among many Agnes Scott buildings that was listed in the National Register of Historic Places.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/agnes-scott-college] Main was built in 1891, making it the oldest building on campus.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/agnes-scott-college] This is documented in the history of Agnes Scott by McNair titled *Lest We Forget* published in 1983.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/agnes-scott-college] As technology became more advanced so did Main.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/agnes-scott-college] Main Hall was the first building on campus and in the neighborhood to have electric lighting.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/agnes-scott-college] Some say that people would gather outside of Main at night just to admire the light shining within the building.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/agnes-scott-college] Built in 1891, the Gazebo at Agnes Scott college has served a multitude of purposes throughout the years.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/agnes-scott-college] It was originally located in front of Agnes Scott (Main) Hall, however in 1926 it was moved to the west end of Rebekah Scott Hall.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/agnes-scott-college] The gazebo has been used as an office, meeting room, meditation chapel, and the Day Student Hut.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/agnes-scott-college] Built in 1906, Rebekah Scott Hall is the second oldest building remaining at Agnes Scott College.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/agnes-scott-college] Rebekah Scott Hall cost $70,000 to build.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/agnes-scott-college] It is named after George Washington Scott's wife, Rebekah Butcher Scott.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/agnes-scott-college] The first floor of Rebekah Scott Hall contains offices, the office of financial aid, and the office of admissions.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/agnes-scott-college] The second and third floors are used as student housing.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/agnes-scott-college] Inman Hall, known commonly as Inman Hall, was built in 1911 and is the oldest building at Agnes Scott College which is used exclusively for student housing.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/agnes-scott-college] In 1985, Inman had major renovations and the third floor was converted into study spaces for students.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/agnes-scott-college] It is made from Indiana limestone and is three stories high.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/agnes-scott-college] The building faces west and has a large veranda which stretches along the front of the building.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/agnes-scott-college] Jennie D, Inman Hall was gifted to Agnes Scott College by Samuel.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/agnes-scott-college] Built in 1923, the Anna Young Alumnae House is dedicated to former science professor and Agnes Scott alumnae, Anna Irwin Young.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/agnes-scott-college] Originally the Alumnae House was a central gathering place for ASC alumnae.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/agnes-scott-college] The house and bedrooms are now used as a campus guest house.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/agnes-scott-college] Behind the house is the Alumnae Garden which houses a statue honoring Robert Frost.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/agnes-scott-college] The Anna Young Alumnae House underwent renovations from 2005 until 2009, after which it was re-opened.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/agnes-scott-college] The Bradley Observatory at Agnes Scott houses the Beck Telescope, a 30-inch (760 mm) Cassegrain reflector, as well as a planetarium with 70-seat capacity and a radio telescope.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/agnes-scott-college] Recently Agnes Scott College and the Georgia Tech Research Institute have collaborated on a project that added a LIDAR facility to the observatory.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/agnes-scott-college] The college's science building, the Bullock Science Center, contains a three-story rendering of part of the nucleotide sequence from Agnes Scott's mitochondrial DNA.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/agnes-scott-college] The DNA came from a blood sample of an ASC alumna who is a direct descendant of the college's namesake.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/agnes-scott-college] Agnes Scott has committed to becoming a carbon-neutral institute by the college's 150th anniversary in 2039 and has taken steps such as partnering with the Clean Air Campaign to reduce its impact on the local environment.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/agnes-scott-college] As of 2015, the college has five solar arrays, four of which are part of Georgia Power's Advanced Solar Initiative.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/agnes-scott-college] The fifth array is on the rooftop of the Bradley Observatory and is also used for student research.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/agnes-scott-college] The renovation of Campbell Hall into a mixed-use residence hall, learning center, and office space was concluded in 2014 and included installation of a hydro-geothermic HVAC system.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/agnes-scott-college] Agnes Scott offers 34 undergraduate majors and 9 graduate and post-baccalaureate programs.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/agnes-scott-college] The undergraduate core curriculum SUMMIT focuses on leadership development, global learning, and digital literacy.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/agnes-scott-college] In 2019, Agnes Scott received the Heiskell Award for Scholars as Drivers of Innovation for its SUMMIT curriculum.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/agnes-scott-college] Undergraduate students are able to cross-register in other ARCHE member institutions.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/agnes-scott-college] The library at Agnes Scott College was an original Carnegie library built in 1910.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/agnes-scott-college] A new library was authorized by the board of trustees in 1935 and opened in the fall of 1936.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/agnes-scott-college] This new library was called the "Carnegie Library" and the original library was turned into a student center.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/agnes-scott-college] It was renamed in 1951 for James McCain, on the occasion of his retirement as the 2nd President of the college.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/agnes-scott-college] As of fall 2025, the student body consists of over 900 undergraduate and graduate students.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/agnes-scott-college] Approximately 60% of undergraduates that year were from Georgia.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/agnes-scott-college] Given Agnes Scott's emphasis on "mak[ing] lifelong friends, shar[ing] unforgettable experiences, discover[ing] meaningful places and find[ing] belonging in [their] community," a majority of students are encouraged to live on campus.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/agnes-scott-college] Thus, most students are expected to live in on-campus housing for all four years as an undergraduate at Agnes Scott College.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/agnes-scott-college] However, the proportion of commuter students has increased (from 15.6 to 18.0 percent between the 2014–2015 and 2019–2020 academic year) due to limited housing caused from an increase in the student population (from 849 to 986 total students) and renovations to the residence halls.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/agnes-scott-college] There are six resident halls situated around the Northern edge of the campus: Winship, Walters, Inman, Rebekah, Campbell, and Agnes Scott Hall (nicknamed "Main").
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/agnes-scott-college] There are over 60 student organizations on campus.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/agnes-scott-college] The college hosts several student publications, including *The Silhouette*, the college's yearbook published annually, and *The Aurora*, Agnes Scott's literary magazine, and *The Profile*, Agnes Scott newspaper.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/agnes-scott-college] All students are invited to join the staff.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/agnes-scott-college] Agnes Scott is a member of the National Collegiate Athletic Association Division III which fields six sports teams including basketball, cross country, soccer, softball, tennis, and volleyball.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/agnes-scott-college] All teams compete in the Collegiate Conference of the South (CCS).
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/agnes-scott-college] Agnes Scott was named as one of the Colleges That Change Lives (CTCL).
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/agnes-scott-college] The campus has been a filming location for many productions, including the filming location for Windsor College in Scream 2, with its campus standing in for the fictional university where Sidney Prescott enrolls to escape her past.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/agnes-scott-college] The college's Gothic architecture, particularly the main hall, provided the backdrop for many scenes, including the gazebo where a key reunion takes place.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/beaux-arts-architecture] The Beaux-Arts style evolved from the French classicism of the Louis XIV style, and then French neoclassicism beginning with the Louis XV style and Louis XVI style.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/beaux-arts-architecture] French architectural styles before the French Revolution were governed by Académie royale d'architecture (1671–1793), then, following the French Revolution, by the Architecture section of the Académie des Beaux-Arts.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/beaux-arts-architecture] The academy held the competition for the Grand Prix de Rome in architecture, which offered prize winners a chance to study the classical architecture of antiquity in Rome.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/beaux-arts-architecture] The formal neoclassicism of the old regime was challenged by four teachers at the academy, Joseph-Louis Duc, Félix Duban, Henri Labrouste, and Léon Vaudoyer, who had studied at the French Academy in Rome at the end of the 1820s.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/beaux-arts-architecture] They wanted to break away from the strict formality of the old style by introducing new models of architecture from the Middle Ages and the Renaissance.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/beaux-arts-architecture] Their goal was to create an authentic French style based on French models.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/beaux-arts-architecture] Their work was aided beginning in 1837 by the creation of the Commission of Historic Monuments, headed by the writer and historian Prosper Mérimée, and by the great interest in the Middle Ages caused by the publication in 1831 of *The Hunchback of Notre-Dame* by Victor Hugo.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/beaux-arts-architecture] The style referred to as *Beaux-Arts* in English reached the apex of its development during the Second Empire (1852–1870) and the Third Republic that followed.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/beaux-arts-architecture] The style of instruction that produced Beaux-Arts architecture continued without major interruption until 1968.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/beaux-arts-architecture] The Beaux-Arts style heavily influenced the architecture of the United States in the period from 1880 to 1920.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/beaux-arts-architecture] In contrast, many European architects of the period 1860–1914 outside France gravitated away from Beaux-Arts and towards their own national academic centers.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/beaux-arts-architecture] Owing to the cultural politics of the late 19th century, British architects of Imperial classicism followed a somewhat more independent course, a development culminating in Sir Edwin Lutyens's New Delhi government buildings.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/beaux-arts-architecture] American architects of the Beaux-Arts generation often returned to Greek models, which had a strong local history in the American Greek Revival of the early 19th century.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/beaux-arts-architecture] For the first time, repertories of photographs supplemented meticulous scale drawings and on-site renderings of details.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/beaux-arts-architecture] Beaux-Arts training made great use of *agrafes*, clasps that link one architectural detail to another; to interpenetration of forms, a Baroque habit; to "speaking architecture" (*architecture parlante*) in which the appropriateness of symbolism was paid particularly close attention.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/beaux-arts-architecture] Beaux-Arts training emphasized the production of quick conceptual sketches, highly finished perspective presentation drawings, close attention to the program, and knowledgeable detailing.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/beaux-arts-architecture] Site considerations included the social and urban context.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/beaux-arts-architecture] Beaux-Arts architecture depended on sculptural decoration along conservative modern lines, employing French and Italian Baroque and Rococo formulas combined with an impressionistic finish and realism.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/beaux-arts-architecture] In the façade shown above, Diana grasps the cornice she sits on in a natural action typical of Beaux-Arts integration of sculpture with architecture.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/beaux-arts-architecture] Slightly overscaled details, bold sculptural supporting consoles, rich deep cornices, swags, and sculptural enrichments in the most bravura finish the client could afford gave employment to several generations of architectural modellers and carvers of Italian and Central European backgrounds.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/beaux-arts-architecture] A sense of appropriate idiom at the craftsman level supported the design teams of the first truly modern architectural offices.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/beaux-arts-architecture] Even though the style was not used as much as in neighbouring country France, some examples of Beaux-Arts buildings can still be found in Belgium.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/beaux-arts-architecture] Furthermore, various large Beaux-Arts buildings can also be found in Brussels on the Avenue Molière/Molièrelaan.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/beaux-arts-architecture] As an old student of the École des Beaux-Arts and as a designer of the Petit Palais, Girault was the figurehead of the Beaux-Arts around the 20th century.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/beaux-arts-architecture] After the death of Alphonse Balat, he became the new and favourite architect of Leopold II of Belgium.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/beaux-arts-architecture] Since Leopold was the grandson of Louis Philippe I of France, he loved this specific building style which is similar to and has its roots in the architecture that has been realized in the 17th and 18th century for the French crown.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/beaux-arts-architecture] They instituted teaching about a variety of architectural styles at the École des Beaux-Arts, and installed fragments of Renaissance and Medieval buildings in the courtyard of the school so students could draw and copy them.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/beaux-arts-architecture] Together, these buildings, drawing upon Renaissance, Gothic and Romanesque and other non-classical styles, broke the monopoly of neoclassical architecture in Paris.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/beaux-arts-architecture] Germany is one of the countries where the Beaux-Arts style was well received, along with Baroque Revival architecture.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/beaux-arts-architecture] The style was especially popular and most prominently featured in the then Kingdom of Prussia during the German Empire.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/beaux-arts-architecture] The best example of Beaux-Arts buildings in Germany today are the Bode Museum in Berlin, and the Laeiszhalle and Hochschule für Musik und Theater Hamburg in Hamburg.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/beaux-arts-architecture] Compared to other countries like France and Germany, the Beaux-Arts style never really became prominent in the Netherlands.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/beaux-arts-architecture] However, a handful of significant buildings have nonetheless been made in this style during the period of 1880 to 1920, mainly being built in the cities of Rotterdam, Amsterdam and The Hague.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/beaux-arts-architecture] In the Romanian Old Kingdom, towards the end of the century, many administrative buildings and private homes are built in the «Beaux-Arts» or «Eclectic» style, brought from France through French architects who came here for work in Romania, schooled in France.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/beaux-arts-architecture] The National Bank of Romania Palace on Strada Lipscani, built between 1883 and 1885 is a good example of this style, decorated not just with columns (mainly Ionic), but also with allegorical statues placed in niches, that depict Agriculture, Industry, Commerce, and Justice.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/beaux-arts-architecture] Because of the popularity of this style, it changed the way Bucharest looks, making it similar in some way with Paris, which led to Bucharest being seen as "Little Paris".
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/beaux-arts-architecture] Eclecticism was very popular not just in Bucharest and Iași, the two biggest cities of Romania at that time, but also in smaller ones like Craiova, Caracal, Râmnicu Vâlcea, Pitești, Ploiești, Buzău, Botoșani, Piatra Neamț, etc.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/beaux-arts-architecture] This style was used not only for administrative palaces and big houses of wealthy people, but also for middle-class homes.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/beaux-arts-architecture] Beaux-Arts was very prominent in public buildings in Canada in the early 20th century.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/beaux-arts-architecture] Notably all three prairie provinces' legislative buildings are in this style.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/beaux-arts-architecture] Beaux-Arts was architecturally relevant in Mexico in the late 19th century and the first decade of 20th century.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/beaux-arts-architecture] The style was popular among the *científicos* of the Porfiriato.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/beaux-arts-architecture] The Academy of San Carlos had an impact on the style's development in Mexico.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/beaux-arts-architecture] Notable architects include Genaro Alcorta, Alfred Giles, and Antonio Rivas Mercado (the preeminent Mexican architect during this era).
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/beaux-arts-architecture] Rivas Mercado served as the director of the Academy of San Carlos from 1903 to 1912.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/beaux-arts-architecture] Having studied at the École des Beaux-Arts in Paris, he aimed to incorporate and adapt its teachings to the Mexican context.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/beaux-arts-architecture] Among the texts produced on the Beaux-Artes style, *Eléments et théorie de l'architecture* from Julien Guadet is said to have had the most influence in Mexico.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/beaux-arts-architecture] The style lost popularity following the Mexican Revolution (beginning in 1910).
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/beaux-arts-architecture] In contemporary architecture, the style has influenced New Classical architect Jorge Loyzaga.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/beaux-arts-architecture] Beaux-Arts architecture had a strong influence on architecture in the United States because of the many prominent American architects who studied at the École des Beaux-Arts, including Henry Hobson Richardson, John Galen Howard, Daniel Burnham, and Louis Sullivan.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/beaux-arts-architecture] The first American architect to attend the École des Beaux-Arts was Richard Morris Hunt, between 1846 and 1855, followed by Henry Hobson Richardson in 1860.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/beaux-arts-architecture] They were followed by an entire generation.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/beaux-arts-architecture] Richardson absorbed Beaux-Arts lessons in massing and spatial planning, then applied them to Romanesque architectural models that were not characteristic of the Beaux-Arts repertory.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/beaux-arts-architecture] His Beaux-Arts training taught him to transcend slavish copying and recreate in the essential fully digested and idiomatic manner of his models.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/beaux-arts-architecture] Richardson evolved a highly personal style (Richardsonian Romanesque) freed of historicism that was influential in early Modernism.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/beaux-arts-architecture] The "White City" of the World's Columbian Exposition of 1893 in Chicago was a triumph of the movement and a major impetus for the short-lived City Beautiful movement in the United States.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/beaux-arts-architecture] The first American university to institute a Beaux-Arts curriculum is the Massachusetts Institute of Technology (MIT) in 1893, when the French architect Constant-Désiré Despradelle was brought to MIT to teach.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/beaux-arts-architecture] The Beaux-Arts curriculum was subsequently begun at Columbia University, the University of Pennsylvania, and elsewhere.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/beaux-arts-architecture] From 1916, the Beaux-Arts Institute of Design in New York City schooled architects, painters, and sculptors to work as active collaborators.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/beaux-arts-architecture] Bosworth; Emory University and Carnegie Mellon University (commissioned in 1908 and 1904, respectively), both designed by Henry Hornbostel; and the University of Texas (commissioned in 1931), designed by Paul Philippe Cret.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/beaux-arts-architecture] While the style of Beaux-Art buildings was adapted from historical models, the construction used the most modern available technology.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/beaux-arts-architecture] The Grand Palais in Paris (1897–1900) had a modern iron frame inside; the classical columns were purely for decoration.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/beaux-arts-architecture] The 1914–1916 construction of the Carolands Chateau south of San Francisco was built to withstand earthquakes, following the devastating 1906 San Francisco earthquake.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/beaux-arts-architecture] The noted Spanish structural engineer Rafael Guastavino (1842–1908), famous for his vaultings, known as Guastavino tile work, designed vaults in dozens of Beaux-Arts buildings in Boston, New York, and elsewhere.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/beaux-arts-architecture] Beaux-Arts architecture also brought a civic face to railroads.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/beaux-arts-architecture] Chicago's Union Station, Detroit's Michigan Central Station, Jacksonville's Union Terminal, Grand Central Terminal and the original Pennsylvania Station in New York, and Washington, D.C.'s Union Station are famous American examples of this style.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/beaux-arts-architecture] Cincinnati has a number of notable Beaux-Arts style buildings, including the Hamilton County Memorial Building in the Over-the-Rhine neighborhood, and the former East End Carnegie library in the Columbia-Tusculum neighborhood.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/beaux-arts-architecture] Two notable ecclesiastical variants on the Beaux-Arts style—both serving the same archdiocese, and both designed by the same architect—stand in the Twin Cities of Minneapolis–Saint Paul, Minnesota.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/beaux-arts-architecture] Mary, the first basilica constructed and consecrated in the United States, was designed by Franco-American architect Emmanuel Louis Masqueray (1861–1917) and opened in 1914.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/beaux-arts-architecture] A year later in neighboring Saint Paul, construction of the massive Masqueray-designed Cathedral of Saint Paul (also known as National Shrine Cathedral of the Apostle Paul) was completed.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/beaux-arts-architecture] The third-largest Roman Catholic cathedral in the United States, its architecture predominantly reflects Beaux-Arts principles, into which Masqueray integrated stylistic elements of other celebrated French churches.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/beaux-arts-architecture] Other examples include the main branch of the New York Public Library; Bancroft Hall at the Naval Academy, the largest academic dormitory in the world; and Michigan Central Station in Detroit, the tallest railway station in the world at the time of completion.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/beaux-arts-architecture] In the late 1800s, during the years when Beaux-Arts architecture was at a peak in France, Americans were one of the largest groups of foreigners in Paris.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/beaux-arts-architecture] Many of them were architects and students of architecture who brought this style back to America.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/beaux-arts-architecture] Charles McKim, William Mead, and Stanford White would ultimately become partners in the prominent architectural firm of McKim, Mead & White, which designed many well-known Beaux-Arts buildings.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/beaux-arts-architecture] From 1880 the so-called Generation of '80 came to power in Argentine politics.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/beaux-arts-architecture] These were admirers of France as a model republic, particularly with regard to culture and aesthetic tastes.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/beaux-arts-architecture] Buenos Aires is a center of Beaux-Arts architecture which continued to be built as late as the 1950s.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/beaux-arts-architecture] Several Australian cities have some significant examples of the style.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/beaux-arts-architecture] It was typically applied to large, solid-looking public office buildings and banks, particularly during the 1920s.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/calhoun-county-courthouse-south-carolina] The **Calhoun County Courthouse**, built in 1913, is a historic courthouse located in the city of St.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/calhoun-county-courthouse-south-carolina] Matthews in Calhoun County, South Carolina.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/calhoun-county-courthouse-south-carolina] It was designed in the Colonial Revival style by Darlington native William Augustus Edwards who designed eight other South Carolina courthouses as well as academic buildings at 12 institutions in Florida, Georgia and South Carolina.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/calhoun-county-courthouse-south-carolina] Calhoun County was created in 1908 and this is its first and only courthouse.
[src:abbeville-county-courthouse/calhoun-county-courthouse-south-carolina] It was listed on the National Register of Historic Places in 1981.
